THE HISTORY OF STANDARDIZED TESTING2Standardized testing has been a part of the American education since the mid-1800. In the1830’s teachers begin to come up with a way that would formally assess student’s achievement(NEA.org. n.d). As the years progressed in 1875, a new testing method was being used tomeasure the mental ability of the students and to see what they’ve learned throughout the yearsin school (NEA.org. n.d). In 1890 Charles William Eliot (Harvard President) proposed thatdifferent test is given to each state.Which makes sense because they did not want the children to have the ability to cheat. Inthe 1900’s the colleges started giving entrance exams to find out if the student was ready forcollege and to see their academic status (NEA.org. n.d). Five years later a French psychologist bythe name of Alfred Binet started developing the standardized test for intelligence which was soonto be combined in the modern IQ test (NEA.org. n.d). In World War 1 they too did standardizetesting that was called the Army Mental Test. Even in the war, you have to make sure that everyman (at that time) was capable of protecting and serving the United States.From 1908 to 1916 Edward Thorndike and his students at Columbia Universitydeveloped the standardized achievement test for arithmetic, handwriting, (which is no longergiven), spelling, reading, and language ability (NEA.org. n.d). I am happy to hear that studentshad some part of creating this test. Nevertheless, by 1925 the U.S. Bureau of Education show thegreat result in doing standardized testing in the student's intelligence as well as their achievementin testing (NEA.org. n.d). After testing students and seeing the positive reaction out of thestandardized testing; the College Board came up with the SAT (Scholastic Aptitude Test) thatwas originally 90 mins and had about 315 question, now who can answer that many problems inan hour in half.
THE HISTORY OF STANDARDIZED TESTING3Now the SAT is three hours long, and it has about 170 questions that are broken up intocategories, writing, math, and critical reading. The SAT and the ACT are now the most popularstandardize testing in today’s education. Furthermore, the SAT and the ACT are only the firststeps that are taken before college. Before 1936 educators were grading the testing by hand, andI’m sure was rather time-consuming. In 1936 the first automatic test scanner was created whichwas called the IBM805, even though this machine has been set up to be helpful, it was also fullof errors as well.The students had to make sure that the circled in the bubbles on their answer key so thecomputer could grade the test correctly. Fast forward to the 21stcentury the No Child LeftBehind Act that mandated each state to give a standardized testing to assess the students and theschool performance (NEA.org. n.d). There are pros and cons to taking the standardized testing.Some students benefit academic wise from the standardized test (ASCD.org. n.d.). However,some student is not great test takers and even if they study the still manage to obtain reducedscores. Standardize testing can also help diagnose a student by finding out he or she has alearning disability (Slavin, 2015).Standardize testing was also unfair and discriminatory against students that did not speakEnglish and special need students (ASCD.org. n.d.). The No Child Left Behind Act made for thekids that did not get the best scores still move on (ASCD.org. n.d.).Like most educators, theywant to ensure that their students are improving and understanding the work that has been givento them. In the meantime some students are still not able to test under pressure and that whatstandardize test create in children from the first grade all the way up to college is incrediblyoverwhelming. Another positive about standardized testing is that it gives the educator an idea ofwhere each student is academically (Slavin, 2015).
THE HISTORY OF STANDARDIZED TESTING4By knowing your students status can help the teacher better prepare the student byfocusing on his and her weakness and polishing their strengths (ASCD.org. n.d.). A standardizedtest is something that is objective to the student's achievement, meaning that the test cannot favora student it can only grade them occurring to the test results (ASCD.org. n.d.). Without thestandardize policy in place could give the teachers the opportunity to be impartial to givingunearned grades to their students. By being graded by a machine keeps the down human errorand is not subjective or bias (ASCD.org. n.d.).Despite these computer generated scores it still cannot compute the student performs overthe years and if a teacher was grading the test and not a machine he or she could take that intoconsideration when grading the student test. That type of thought can go a long when a childstudies so hard but still come up short. These test can be a significant cause of depression,especially when that student know that they did everything right. On the contrary, there are about20 school systems that have achieved significant, and sustained international assessmentsthrough the standardized testing by monitoring the system progress (ASCD.org. n.d.).On average from pre-k to 12thgrade a child may take a total of 113 standardized testwhich most of them are not graded but are put in place to evaluate where the student isacademically. It is tough to say really how many each stat take but I do know that it does have tobe annual. I sometimes worry about the number of tests that my son takes in son because he isstill struggling in math and reading. It just might be too many standardized tests to be worriedabout. Yes as parents we want our children social and academically ready for the word, but wealso do want them to feel bad that they are not great test takers. Standardize testing is federallymandated.
